## Layer 2 — Cleaning and Feature Engineering

This is the most critical layer. Most competing systems use static 
features — current GPA, current attendance rate. We use trend 
features that capture change over time.

The insight: a student going from 3.8 to 2.8 GPA is in a 
completely different situation from a student who has always 
had 2.8 GPA. Static features see them as identical. 
Trend features see the difference immediately.

### Cleaning approach

Every null value is classified before any action is taken:

| Null type | Meaning | Treatment |
|---|---|---|
| Random missing | Data pipeline error | Impute with student's personal mean |
| Structural absence | First semester, no prior data | Leave null, add is_first_semester flag |
| Meaningful absence | Student stopped engaging | Forward fill, add imputed flag |
| Inapplicable | Full scholarship, no financial data | Fill zero, add not_applicable flag |

A parallel flag column is created for every imputed value.
The model sees both the filled value and the fact it was filled.

### Features engineered

Academic trend features:
- grade_slope_4w — linear regression slope of GPA over 4 weeks
- grade_slope_8w — linear regression slope of GPA over 8 weeks
- semester_grade_delta — this semester GPA minus last semester GPA

Attendance trend features:
- attendance_delta — current week rate minus student's own 8-week baseline
- absenteeism_trend — rate of change in weekly unexcused absences

Financial stress features:
- financial_stress_index — weighted score combining payment history,
  aid status changes, fee waiver applications, and outstanding balance
- consecutive_late_payments — count of back-to-back late payments

Engagement features:
- engagement_recency — days since last non-academic activity
- engagement_no_history — binary flag for students with zero records

### Why personal baseline for attendance

Comparing a student against the class average misses individual 
deterioration. A student who always attends 60% and drops to 55% 
is probably fine. A student who always attends 95% and drops to 
70% is in serious trouble.

Attendance delta is computed against each student's own history —
not the cohort average. This catches individual decline regardless 
of starting point and is fairer across socioeconomic groups.

### The cascading signal story

These features are not independent. They tell a cascading story:

Financial stress hits first — a family situation changes.
Weeks later, absenteeism rises — extra shifts, family responsibilities.
Weeks after that, grades fall — the semester delta turns negative.

A student where only the financial stress index has spiked but 
grades and attendance are still fine is in the earliest chapter —
where intervention has the highest chance of success.

