## Layer 3 — Risk Scoring Model

### Model choice

Algorithm: XGBoost gradient boosted trees
Output: continuous risk score from 0.0 to 1.0

XGBoost is chosen over deep learning approaches because:
- Handles tabular data with mixed types naturally
- Produces well-calibrated probabilities
- SHAP values are computationally tractable
- Interpretable to technical stakeholders

### Key design decisions

Time decay weighting
Recent observations carry higher sample weight during training.
A grade drop last week matters more than one six months ago.
This is enforced through sample weights, not feature engineering.

Asymmetric loss function
False negatives — missing a student who drops out — are penalized 
3x more than false positives — flagging a student unnecessarily.
This reflects the real-world cost asymmetry of the two error types.

Temporal train-test split
Training uses early semesters. Testing uses later semesters.
No student's future data ever appears in their own training window.
Standard random splits are not used — they leak future information.

Calibrated probabilities
Isotonic regression is applied post-training so that a score of 
0.7 genuinely means approximately 70% dropout probability.
This makes the risk score meaningful and communicable.

### Experiment tracking

All model runs tracked in MLflow:
- Parameters logged per run
- Metrics logged: AUC-PR, F1, FNR, FPR per demographic group
- Best model registered in MLflow Model Registry
- Artifacts stored for reproducibility

