## Layer 4 — Fairness Audit

Fairness is not an offline evaluation in this system. It is part 
of the prediction pipeline. Every prediction passes through the 
fairness audit before reaching the output table.

### The problem we are solving

A model trained on historical data inherits historical inequities.
If low-income students dropped out more often in the past — not 
because they were less capable but because they had fewer resources —
the model learns to flag them more aggressively.

This creates two simultaneous failures:
- Low-income students get over-flagged — stigmatized, resources wasted
- Higher-income struggling students get under-flagged — fall through cracks

A single accuracy number never reveals this. Equalized odds does.

### Fairness metric: equalized odds

We separately compute for each demographic group:

False Positive Rate — of students who did not drop out,
what fraction did we wrongly flag as high risk?

False Negative Rate — of students who did drop out,
what fraction did we miss entirely?

Equalized odds requires both FPR and FNR to be within 5% 
tolerance across gender groups and socioeconomic bands.

### Correction method

When gaps exceed tolerance:

Group-specific threshold adjustment — instead of one global 
threshold for everyone, each group gets the threshold that 
achieves the target FPR for that group.

Training reweighting — underrepresented groups receive higher 
sample weights during training so their errors cost more.

### Fairness output

Every student in the intervention table carries a fairness flag:

Verified — prediction made under a fair, group-calibrated threshold
Review needed — fairness gap detected for this student's group,
manual counselor verification recommended before acting

